.TH "polyglot\-starters" "7" "" "Runtime Documentation" "Polyglot Devcontainers"
.SH NAME
polyglot\-starters \- choose the right starter or proving path
.SH PURPOSE
This page explains which starter path to use and how the published
starter images behave when opened into an empty workspace.
.SH WHEN TO USE
Read this page when you want to start real work and need to choose the
correct starter.
.SH PRIMARY COMMANDS
.IP
.EX
task init
task ci
task scenarios:verify
man polyglot\-python
man polyglot\-java
man polyglot\-troubleshooting
.EE
.SH WORKFLOW
Use these paths for practical starts:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]templates/python\-secure\f[R] Preferred Python starter template.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]templates/python\-node\-secure\f[R] Preferred published\-image
starter for Python plus Node / TypeScript.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]templates/java\-secure\f[R] Preferred Java starter template.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]examples/python\-image\-example\f[R] Use when you want to validate
the published Python image consumption path.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]examples/java\-image\-example\f[R] Use when you want to validate
the published Java image consumption path.
.PP
Published starter image workflow:
.IP "1." 3
mount an empty or nearly empty workspace
.IP "2." 3
open the published image
.IP "3." 3
run \f[CR]task init\f[R]
.IP "4." 3
let the starter scaffold the local project files
.IP "5." 3
run \f[CR]task ci\f[R]
.IP "6." 3
optionally run \f[CR]task scenarios:verify\f[R] for a compact starter
proof
.PP
Starter image behavior:
.IP \(bu 2
the image already contains the runtime, package managers, scanners, and
local man pages
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]task init\f[R] installs project\-local dependencies into the
mounted workspace
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]task init\f[R] may create \f[CR].venv\f[R],
\f[CR]node_modules\f[R], \f[CR].gradle\f[R], lockfile\-backed caches,
and \f[CR].artifacts\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
the workspace does not need to be a Git repository before
\f[CR]task init\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
the \f[CR]python\-node\-secure\f[R] starter also exposes starter\-local
scenario tasks after bootstrap
.PP
Treat these differently:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]examples/python\-maintenance\-example\f[R] A proving fixture for
dependency maintenance experiments.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]examples/java\-maintenance\-example\f[R] A proving fixture for
Java dependency maintenance experiments.
.SH OUTPUTS / ARTIFACTS
Starters and examples write artifacts under their own
\f[CR].artifacts/scans/\f[R] directories.
.SH COMMON FAILURES
.IP \(bu 2
Starting from a proving fixture when you only needed a clean starter.
.IP \(bu 2
Expecting a published starter image to contain your project files before
running \f[CR]task init\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
Expecting \f[CR]task init\f[R] to be a no\-op in a fresh mounted
workspace.
.IP \(bu 2
Treating image\-consumption examples as the same thing as authoring
templates.
.SH GUIDANCE
.IP \(bu 2
For a new Python project, start from \f[CR]python\-secure\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
For a new Python plus Node / TypeScript project, start from
\f[CR]python\-node\-secure\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
For a new Java project, start from \f[CR]java\-secure\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
Use image examples when you are validating the published container path.
.IP \(bu 2
When consuming a published starter image directly, keep the mounted
workspace effectively empty until bootstrap completes.
.IP \(bu 2
In \f[CR]python\-node\-secure\f[R], use \f[CR]task scenarios:verify\f[R]
when you want a starter\-local proof of the task contract, security
artifacts, and non\-git secret\-scan fallback.
